"""
MKT Christ Commentary — John chapters 14–16
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-john-14-16.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/john.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/john.json (MKT text for quoting)
- data/parallels/john.json (no ch14-16 parallels found)
- data/translation/glossary-greek.json (paraklētos, alētheia, hodos, agapaō, menō)

Key decisions in this range:
- Author referred to as "the Evangelist"; Jesus as "Jesus" or "the Son"
- 14:6 ("I am the way, the truth, and the life"): classified as direct revelation — the sixth of
  the seven Johannine "I am" statements with predicate; the exclusive claim about mediation is
  retained without softening; it fulfills the OT priest/Torah/life vocabulary
- 14:16-17 (the Advocate/Paraclete): classified as direct revelation — the trinitarian promise
  that the Spirit is "another" advocate of the same kind as Jesus; the Spirit's coming is the
  continuation of Christ's presence, not a replacement by a lesser power
- 14:28 ("the Father is greater than I"): classified as revelation of God — this is the economic
  subordination of the sent Son relative to the sending Father, not an ontological inferiority;
  read in the context of the sending-and-return framework of John
- 15:1 ("I am the true vine"): classified as direct revelation — the seventh I AM with predicate;
  the vine typology activates Isa 5, Ps 80, Jer 2, Ezek 15 (Israel as faithless vine); Christ
  is the true vine replacing the unfaithful one
- 15:13 ("lay down one's life for one's friends"): classified as direct revelation — the
  definition of the cross; the supreme expression of the love command (15:12)
- 15:25 (Ps 69:4): classified as direct fulfillment — the Evangelist cites it explicitly
- 16:7 ("it is for your good that I am going away"): classified as direct revelation — the
  departure-enabling-Spirit logic is Christological; the Spirit's presence is greater good than
  the earthly presence of the pre-resurrection Christ
- 16:8-11 (Spirit convicts of sin, righteousness, judgment): each classified as direct revelation
  — three Christological definitions given by the Spirit's conviction work
- 16:28 ("I came from the Father..."): classified as direct revelation — the fullest single-sentence
  Christological ontology in the Gospel; the arc of the incarnation stated plainly
- 16:33 ("I have overcome the world"): classified as direct revelation — perfect tense of
  accomplished victory; the cross as the defeat of the world-system, not Christ's defeat
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOHN = {
  "14": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: "You believe in God; believe also in me." The parallel construction — the same faith directed at God and at Christ — is the Christological claim of the farewell discourses in embryo. The disciples must not let their hearts be troubled because the one who speaks is not less than the God they already trust. The command to believe in Jesus with the same trust directed to God the Father is the same claim as 5:23 (equal honor to Son and Father). The Farewell Discourses open with the demand that Christ himself be the object of the disciples\' ultimate trust.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: the Father\'s house with many rooms is the language of the heavenly dwelling — not earthly hospitality but the eschatological home. "I am going there to prepare a place for you" connects to the priestly work of Christ: the High Priest who enters the most holy place to prepare the way for others (Heb 6:19–20). The prepared place is the inheritance that the ascended Son makes available; the Father\'s house is what the temple and tabernacle always shadowed — the dwelling of God with his people that will be permanent in the new creation (Rev 21:3).</p>',
    "3": '<p>A direct revelation: "I will come back and take you to be with me that you also may be where I am." The promise of Christ\'s return — the parousia — is here given in its most personal form: not a coming to execute judgment but a coming to collect and bring home. The purpose of the return is union with Christ: "that you also may be where I am." The eschatological goal of the entire plan of redemption is co-presence with the Son in the Father\'s house — the same goal that Jesus\' High Priestly prayer will express ("I want those you have given me to be with me where I am," 17:24).</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "You know the way to the place where I am going." The statement anticipates Thomas\'s protest (v5) and sets up the I AM declaration of v6. The disciples do know the way — not as a path they can find independently, but as a person they already know. The Evangelist constructs the exchange so that Thomas\'s honest confession of not-knowing is the opening for the most comprehensive Christological claim in the chapter.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: Thomas\'s "we don\'t know where you are going, so how can we know the way?" is the honest incomprehension that the Evangelist consistently uses to open the space for deeper disclosure. Thomas does not pretend to understand; his question is the right question, which receives the most direct answer in the Gospel. The one who asks plainly receives plainly. Thomas\'s doubt-shaped questions throughout the Gospel (11:16; 14:5; 20:24–28) consistently lead to Christological revelation.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A direct revelation — the sixth of the seven Johannine "I am" statements: "I am the way, the truth, and the life. No one comes to the Father except through me." The three nouns are not three parallel claims but a single, mutually interpreting whole: the way to the Father is the truth about God and the life of God embodied in one person. The OT background is rich: the "way" of the Lord (Torah, covenant, Wisdom in Prov 8); the truth of God (divine faithfulness, <em>emet</em>); the life that God gives. All three converge in Christ alone. The exclusive claim ("no one except through me") is not the arrogance of one among many options but the statement of the only bridge between a fallen world and the holy God.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "If you really know me, you will know my Father as well. From now on, you do know him and have seen him." The epistemological inseparability of the Son and Father — to know one is to know the other — is stated as a present accomplished fact: the disciples who have been with Jesus have been in the presence of the Father\'s self-disclosure. The "from now on" marks the hinge: with the coming of the Son, the era of indirect knowledge of God through types and shadows has ended. Direct knowledge of the Father comes through the Son.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: Philip\'s request — "show us the Father and that will be enough for us" — is the honest expression of the disciples\' deepest longing and their persistent failure to grasp that it has already been met. They are asking for what they have had all along without recognizing it. The Evangelist presents the request as both touching and misguided — the Father has been present in the Son throughout the ministry, and yet the disciples have not connected what they have seen with who the Father is.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct revelation: "Anyone who has seen me has seen the Father." The most direct statement of the Son as the image and revelation of the Father in the farewell discourses. The Evangelist has been building to this since 1:18 ("the one and only Son... has made him known"). The one who looks at Jesus looks at the Father\'s character, will, love, and judgment — because the Son is the perfect embodiment of the Father\'s own life and being (cf. Col 1:15; Heb 1:3). To ask for the Father beyond the Son is to misunderstand the nature of the incarnation.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "I am in the Father, and the Father is in me." The mutual indwelling of the Trinitarian persons — the perichoresis — is the Evangelist\'s description of the relationship that grounds the Son\'s complete identity with the Father\'s will and words. The Father living in the Son and doing his work through the Son means that every act and word of Jesus is the Father\'s act and word. The words Jesus speaks are not his own; the works he does are the Father\'s works enacted through the Son. This is the basis of Christ\'s absolute authority.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "at least believe on the evidence of the works themselves." The works — the seven signs — are the Father\'s testimony to the Son (5:36). Belief can proceed from the personal knowledge of Jesus or from the evidence of the works he has done; both routes lead to the same destination. The Evangelist has consistently presented the signs as pointing to who Jesus is rather than being ends in themselves. Even the lowest form of faith — based on works rather than the word — is genuine faith if it reaches its destination in believing that Jesus is who he claims to be.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "whoever believes in me will do the works I have been doing, and they will do even greater things than these, because I am going to the Father." The "greater works" are not superior miracles but the expanded scope of the mission through the Spirit after Pentecost: the conversion of thousands in Acts 2–4, the gathering of the Gentiles, the global spread of the gospel. Christ accomplishes these through his disciples by the Spirit. The departure enables the "greater works" because the glorified Christ sends the Spirit who empowers the mission beyond the geographical limitations of the incarnation.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: "whatever you ask in my name... so that the Father may be glorified in the Son." Prayer in Christ\'s name is not a verbal formula but prayer that is shaped by the character and purposes of Christ — prayer consistent with who he is and what he is doing. The purpose of answered prayer is the Father\'s glorification in the Son: the mission continues through the disciples\' prayer-shaped ministry, and the Father is honored through the ongoing work of the Son in and through them.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: "You may ask me for anything in my name, and I will do it." The repetition intensifies the promise — the exalted Christ continues to act in response to the disciples\' prayers offered in his name. The one who has gone to the Father has not withdrawn from the disciples\' situation; he remains active on their behalf. This is the Evangelist\'s version of the NT intercession theology: the ascended Christ continues to work through prayer (Heb 7:25 — "always lives to intercede for them").</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "If you love me, keep my commands." Love and obedience are not alternatives in the Johannine ethic — love is what motivates obedience, and obedience is what demonstrates love. The pattern mirrors the Son\'s relationship to the Father (15:10 — "I have kept my Father\'s commands and remain in his love"). Discipleship is not rule-following but love-expressing. The commands of Christ are the shape that love takes in practice; to keep them is to participate in the pattern of Christ\'s own love for the Father.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A direct revelation: "I will ask the Father, and he will give you another advocate (<em>paraklētos</em>) to help you and be with you forever." The Spirit is "another" (<em>allos</em>) Paraclete — another of the same kind as Christ himself (who is implicitly the first Paraclete, cf. 1 John 2:1). The Spirit is not a lesser power or a consolation prize for Christ\'s absence but the continuation of Christ\'s own presence and advocacy in a new mode. The promise of the Spirit is the promise that Christ will not ultimately leave his disciples but will remain with them through the Spirit.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct revelation: "the Spirit of truth" — the Spirit is identified by his relationship to the truth that is Christ (14:6). The Spirit\'s function is to bear witness to and extend the truth of Christ; he does not introduce new revelation but makes the revelation of Christ fully accessible (14:26; 16:13–14). The world cannot receive the Spirit of truth because it has not received Christ who is the truth. The disciples receive the Spirit because they have received Christ; the Spirit is the continuation and deepening of their knowledge of him.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: "I will not leave you as orphans; I will come to you." The promise of Christ\'s return applies both to the resurrection appearances (which the disciples will experience in a "little while," 16:16–22) and to the ongoing presence of Christ through the Spirit. The Father who does not leave his people to orphanhood (Ps 68:5 — "a father to the fatherless") is now the Son making the same promise. The disciples who will flee and scatter at the arrest will discover that the risen Christ comes to them rather than abandoning them.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A direct revelation: "Because I live, you also will live." The resurrection life of Christ — which the Father has granted to the Son who has life in himself (5:26) — is shared with believers. The causal connection ("because I live, you will live") makes the disciples\' life derivative from and dependent on the life of Christ. The resurrection of believers is grounded in the resurrection of Christ; they do not have life in themselves but participate in his indestructible life. This is the basis of the NT theology of union with Christ in his resurrection (Rom 6:5; 1 Cor 15:22; Col 3:3–4).</p>',
    "20": '<p>A direct revelation: "On that day you will realize that I am in my Father, and you are in me, and I am in you." The trinitarian mutual indwelling extends to include the disciples: the relationship of the Father and Son that has governed the entire Gospel now becomes the framework within which believers exist. Union with Christ ("you are in me") and Christ\'s indwelling ("I am in you") are the double-sided experience of what it means to belong to the Son. The "that day" is the post-resurrection era opened by the Spirit, in which this union is known rather than merely promised.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "I too will love them and show myself to them." The self-disclosure of Christ to the obedient lover — the one who has and keeps his commands — is the promise of ongoing Christological revelation beyond the earthly ministry. The post-resurrection appearances are the first instance; the Spirit-mediated knowledge of Christ is the ongoing form. The promise is that the Son does not withdraw after the resurrection but continues to make himself known to those who love him.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A theme: Judas (not Iscariot) asks why Jesus will not show himself to the world. The question is the honest perplexity about the selective disclosure — why should the Messiah not reveal himself universally? Jesus\' answer (v23) will not directly address the "why" but will describe the conditions under which the self-disclosure occurs: love and obedience create the receptivity without which revelation cannot be received. The Son does not withhold himself from the world to be exclusive; the world\'s unwillingness to receive him is the obstacle, not any divine preference for secrecy.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "We will come to them and make our home with them." The Father and Son making their home (<em>monē</em> — the same word as "rooms" in v2) with the believer is the realized eschatology of the Temple theology: what the temple symbolized (the dwelling of God with his people) is now enacted in individual believers through the Spirit. The divine indwelling promised throughout the OT (Ezek 37:27 — "my dwelling place will be with them"; Zech 2:10 — "I will come and dwell in your midst") is fulfilled not in a building but in the community of love and obedience.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: "Anyone who does not love me will not obey my teaching. These words you hear are not my own; they belong to the Father who sent me." The dual claim — rejection of Christ\'s words is rejection of the Father\'s words — is the Christological principle that governs the judgment of the world. There is no access to the Father\'s word except through the Son who carries it. To dismiss Jesus\' teaching as merely human opinion is to dismiss the Father who spoke it through him.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: "All this I have spoken while still with you." The Evangelist marks the end of the earthly teaching ministry — what has been given in the incarnation is complete in itself. But the Spirit\'s work (v26) will take what has been given and make it fully accessible. The teaching of the incarnate Son is not superseded by the Spirit\'s work; it is illuminated, remembered, and applied. The farewell discourses are simultaneously the conclusion of the earthly teaching and the foundation of all Spirit-guided teaching to come.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A direct revelation: "the Advocate, the Holy Spirit, whom the Father will send in my name, will teach you all things and will remind you of everything I have said to you." The Spirit\'s work is explicitly Christological: the Spirit does not introduce new revelation but teaches and reminds of Christ\'s revelation. "Sent in my name" means the Spirit represents Christ and acts on his behalf — carrying his authority. "Will remind you of everything I have said" is the promise that grounds the apostolic memory behind the Gospels: the Spirit\'s role in preserving and interpreting the words of Jesus for the church.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct revelation: "Peace I leave with you; my peace I give you. I do not give to you as the world gives." The priestly blessing of Numbers 6:24–26 — "the LORD... give you peace" — is here fulfilled by the Son who grants what the priests could only ask for. But the peace he gives is not the world\'s peace (absence of conflict, social harmony, political stability) but the eschatological shalom of the kingdom — the peace that "surpasses all understanding" (Phil 4:7) because it is grounded in the Son\'s accomplished work rather than in circumstances. The one who is about to be arrested and killed leaves peace as his legacy.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A revelation of God: "the Father is greater than I." The statement is set in the context of the Son\'s going away and coming back — the economic subordination of the sent Son relative to the sending Father within the mission. In the framework of John\'s Christology, this is not an ontological inferiority (the Son is equal to the Father in 5:18; 10:30) but the relational structure of the sending: the one who is sent is in that respect less than the one who sends. The disciples\' gladness at his going (to the Father, where he belongs) should outweigh their grief. The departure is not loss but completion of the mission within the proper order.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of God: "I have told you now before it happens, so that when it does happen you will believe." The pattern of prophecy-then-fulfillment as the ground of faith is the logic of the OT prophetic tradition applied to Christ\'s own predictions. He tells the disciples what is coming — the betrayal (13:19), the cross, the resurrection, the Spirit — so that when it occurs they will have a reason to believe beyond their immediate experience. The foreknowledge disclosed in prophecy is itself a sign of divine identity.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A direct revelation: "the prince of this world is coming. He has no hold over me." The adversary who has entered Judas (13:27) and who drives the passion is approaching; and the Son makes the definitive claim: the adversary has no claim on him, no foothold, no power. The sinlessness of Christ (Heb 4:15) means the adversary cannot exploit the same vulnerability he exploited in every other human being. The passion is not the world-ruler\'s victory over Christ; it is Christ willingly entering the adversary\'s domain to defeat it from within.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of God: "but he comes so that the world may learn that I love the Father and do exactly what my Father has commanded me." The cross is the ultimate demonstration of the Son\'s love for the Father and his perfect obedience to the Father\'s will. What the passion will display to the world — even in its cruelty and apparent victory — is the character of the Son: his love, his obedience, his surrender of himself in accordance with the Father\'s command. "Come now; let us leave" — the departure to Gethsemane and the cross begins.</p>'
  },
  "15": {
    "1": '<p>A direct revelation — the seventh of the Johannine "I am" statements with a predicate: "I am the true vine, and my Father is the gardener." The vine is Israel\'s most consistent self-image in the OT: Isaiah 5:1–7 (the vineyard that produced only bad fruit and was destroyed), Psalm 80:8–16 (the vine brought out of Egypt and now withering), Jeremiah 2:21 (the vine turned wild and degenerate), Ezekiel 15 (the vine wood useless except to burn). Jesus is the "true" (<em>alēthinos</em>) vine — the real one, the one the OT vines shadowed and failed to be. He is what Israel was called to be, and through union with him his disciples bear the fruit Israel could not.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "every branch that does bear fruit he prunes so that it will be even more fruitful." The Father\'s role as the gardener who cuts and prunes is the OT theme of divine discipline for the purpose of greater fruitfulness — not judgment but cultivation. The pruning of the branches is the suffering and discipline that the NT associates with sonship (Heb 12:5–11). The Father does not abandon the branches that bear fruit; he invests in them more intensively. The suffering the disciples will experience (15:18–21; 16:2) is the Father\'s pruning, not his rejection.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "You are already clean because of the word I have spoken to you." The word of Christ is the agent of the disciples\' cleansing — a cleansing equivalent to the pruning of the vine. The connection between word and purification runs through the OT (Ps 119:9 — "How can a young man keep his way pure? By keeping your word") and the NT (Eph 5:26 — "cleansing her by the washing with water through the word"). Christ\'s word has accomplished in the disciples what the foot-washing enacted: they are clean through the word he has spoken over their lives.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "Remain in me, as I also remain in you. No branch can bear fruit by itself." The word <em>menō</em> (remain/abide) is the Johannine keyword for the ongoing union with Christ that characterizes authentic discipleship. The mutual abiding — the branch in the vine and the vine in the branch — is the structural description of what it means to be in Christ. The inability of the branch to bear fruit apart from the vine is the Evangelist\'s statement of the believer\'s total ontological dependence on Christ for any fruitfulness in the kingdom.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct revelation: "I am the vine; you are the branches. If you remain in me and I in you, you will bear much fruit; apart from me you can do nothing." The positive and negative of the vine theology stated together: union with Christ produces abundant fruit; separation from Christ produces nothing. "Can do nothing" (<em>ouden dynasai</em>) is the absolute: not "little," but zero. The disciples\' fruitfulness is not their own achievement supplemented by Christ; it is entirely the fruit of the vine flowing through the branches. This is the Christological grounding of all genuine Christian life and ministry.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: the severed branch "is picked up, thrown into the fire and burned." The judgment on non-abiding is the consequence of the vine-theology: the branch that does not remain in Christ has no life source and withers; the withered branch is combustible and destined for fire. The Evangelist does not elaborate a full doctrine of apostasy here but provides the vine-image\'s natural consequence. Those who were "in the vine" but did not abide — who made no lasting union with Christ — discover that their connection was formal rather than vital.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "If you remain in me and my words remain in you, ask whatever you wish, and it will be done for you." Prayer is conditioned on abiding — the branch in constant connection with the vine asks for what the vine would ask for. The mutual indwelling of the disciple in Christ and Christ\'s word in the disciple ensures that requests will be shaped by Christ\'s own will and the Father\'s purposes. The prayer that is answered is not any wish but the desire that flows from genuine union with Christ — prayers that arise from abiding are prayers that the Father delights to answer.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "This is to my Father\'s glory, that you bear much fruit, showing yourselves to be my disciples." The fruit-bearing of the disciples is not for their own benefit or Christ\'s reputation but for the Father\'s glory — the same purpose that governs all of Christ\'s own ministry (12:28; 13:31–32; 17:4). The disciples\' fruitfulness is the continuation and extension of the Son\'s mission of glorifying the Father. The vine lives for the glory of the gardener; the branches live for the glory of the vine and the gardener.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "As the Father has loved me, so have I loved you. Now remain in my love." The Son\'s love for the disciples is measured by the same scale as the Father\'s love for the Son — the eternal covenant love that preceded the world (17:24). The disciples are invited not merely to experience love but to remain in it, to inhabit it as the vine inhabits the soil. The love of the Father for the Son and the love of the Son for the disciples are the same quality and origin — the divine love that defines all genuine love in the NT (1 John 4:19).</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "If you keep my commands, you will remain in my love, just as I have kept my Father\'s commands and remain in his love." Christ\'s own obedience to the Father\'s commands — which has been the consistent pattern of the Johannine Jesus (5:19; 8:29; 12:49; 14:31) — is here offered as the model for the disciples\' obedience to Christ\'s commands. The Son remains in the Father\'s love through obedience; the disciples remain in the Son\'s love through obedience. The same structure of love-and-obedience runs from the Father through the Son to the disciples.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "I have told you this so that my joy may be in you and that your joy may be complete." The joy the Son has in the Father — the fullness of the divine communion — is what he desires for his disciples. The Johannine vision of salvation is not merely the removal of condemnation but participation in the joy of the Trinity. "Complete joy" (<em>plēroō</em>) is the fullness of the eschatological gladness that the OT associated with the messianic age (Isa 35:10; 51:11; 61:7) — now given through union with the Son.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A direct revelation: "My command is this: Love each other as I have loved you." The love command is given specific content through the standard: "as I have loved you." The measure of Christ\'s love is the cross (v13) — the laying down of his life. The love the disciples are commanded to show each other is therefore not sentiment or affection but the same cruciform shape that Christ\'s love took: willing self-sacrifice for the good of the other. The command is not an exhortation to feel warmly toward one another but an invitation into the same self-giving pattern that defines Christ\'s own love.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct revelation: "Greater love has no one than this: to lay down one\'s life for one\'s friends." The supreme expression of love is defined by what Christ is about to do at the cross. The statement is universal in form ("no one") and specific in application: Jesus is defining the love he himself will enact within hours. The cross is not an accident or a tragedy; it is the greatest act of love in human history, accomplished by the one who has just described its logic. The Evangelist positions this statement at the center of the vine discourse because the cross is the vine\'s life poured out for the branches.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: "You are my friends if you do what I command." The elevation from servant to friend is the movement from unknowing obedience to knowing participation in the Son\'s mission. The condition — doing what he commands — is not a means of earning the status but the evidence of the reality. Those who are genuinely united to Christ will naturally do what flows from that union; the friendship is evidenced by obedience just as the branch\'s connection to the vine is evidenced by fruit-bearing.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "I have called you friends, for everything that I learned from my Father I have made known to you." The friendship is defined by the disclosure of the Father\'s purposes — what the Son has received from the Father, the disciples receive from the Son. The chain of revelation (Father → Son → disciples) that runs through John is here named as the ground of friendship: servants do not know their master\'s business; friends share it. The disciples are now privy to the redemptive purposes of God — the knowledge that defines their status and mission.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A direct revelation: "You did not choose me, but I chose you and appointed you so that you might go and bear fruit — fruit that will last." The sovereign initiative of the Son in election — he chose the disciples, not the reverse — grounds the disciples\' security and mission. They are not following their own religious enthusiasm; they are sent by the one who has chosen them for this specific purpose: lasting fruit. The fruit that lasts is the fruit that persists into the age to come — lives transformed by the gospel, not temporary religious impact. The election of the disciples is the election of the church for its mission in the world.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: "This is my command: Love each other." The repetition of the love command (cf. v12) underlines its centrality in the farewell discourses. Having spoken of friendship, election, and the knowledge imparted by the Son, Jesus returns to the single practice that defines the community: love for one another. The Evangelist presents love not as one virtue among others but as the comprehensive practice in which union with the true vine is expressed and the Father is glorified (v8).</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: "If the world hates you, keep in mind that it hated me first." The disciples\' experience of the world\'s hostility is not a sign that something has gone wrong but a participation in the pattern of the Son\'s own experience. The Servant of Isaiah 53 who is "despised and rejected" (Isa 53:3) experiences the world\'s hostility; those who belong to the Servant share the Servant\'s reception. The cross is the paradigmatic act of the world\'s hatred toward the Son, and the disciples\' persecution is the ongoing form of that same hostility directed at the Son through his community.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "I have chosen you out of the world. That is why the world hates you." Election is the source of both the disciples\' identity and the world\'s hostility. Those who have been chosen out of the world no longer belong to the world\'s system of values and loyalties — and the world resents this. The logic is the same as the OT prophetic experience: those who speak God\'s word are rejected by those who prefer the world\'s word. The community of Christ is not a subset of the world but a distinct people drawn out of it by the Son\'s choosing.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "If they persecuted me, they will persecute you also. If they obeyed my teaching, they will obey yours also." The pattern of reception the disciples will experience mirrors Christ\'s own — in both directions. The same people who rejected the Son will reject his messengers; the same people who received the Son\'s word will receive the apostolic word. The disciples\' mission is an extension of the Son\'s mission, and its reception follows the same division that the Son\'s presence produced (cf. Luke 12:51).</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "They will treat you this way because of my name, for they do not know the one who sent me." The persecution occurs "because of my name" — the name that carries the authority and identity of the Son. Rejection of the disciples\' witness is ultimately rejection of the Son, which is rejection of the Father who sent him. The root of the world\'s hostility is not personal antagonism but the ontological incompatibility between the world that does not know God and the disciples who bear the name of the one God has sent.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: "Now they have no excuse for their sin." The coming of Christ has irrevocably changed the moral situation of those who have heard him. Before the incarnation, ignorance was possible; after it, the revelation is so full and clear that refusal is deliberate. This is the judicial weight of the incarnation: it does not merely offer salvation but closes the path to the excuse of not knowing. Those who reject Christ after hearing him reject with full knowledge, and their rejection carries the weight of that knowledge.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "Whoever hates me hates my Father as well." The inseparability of the response to the Son and the response to the Father is stated here in its negative form — hatred of the Son is hatred of the Father. The principle of sent-and-sender identification (13:20 — receiving the disciples is receiving Christ; receiving Christ is receiving the Father) applies to rejection as well: the world\'s hostility to the Son is hostility to God himself, whether the world acknowledges this or not.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: "If I had not done among them the works no one else did, they would not be guilty of sin." The uniqueness of Christ\'s works — signs that no other agent of God performed — raises the moral stakes of the world\'s rejection. The greater the evidence, the greater the culpability of those who refuse it. The signs were not ambiguous; they were decisive disclosures of divine action (5:36 — "the works the Father has given me to finish"). Those who have seen works "no one else did" and still hate both the Son and the Father have exhausted the possibilities of evidence.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "this is to fulfill what is written in their Law: They hated me without reason." The Evangelist cites Psalm 69:4 ("those who hate me without reason outnumber the hairs of my head") as fulfilled in the world\'s hostility to Christ. Psalm 69 is one of the most heavily Christologically applied psalms in the NT (cited in connection with the temple cleansing in John 2:17; with the vinegar on the cross in John 19:29). The unmerited hatred that the psalmist describes — suffering for no cause of his own — is fully enacted in the world\'s rejection of the sinless Son.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A direct revelation: "When the Advocate comes, whom I will send to you from the Father — the Spirit of truth who goes out from the Father — he will testify about me." The Spirit\'s sending is described in trinitarian terms: the Son sends the Spirit; the Spirit goes out from the Father. Both the Son and the Father are the source of the Spirit\'s mission. The Spirit\'s primary work in the world is testimony about Christ — confirming who Jesus is and what he has done. The Spirit does not testify about himself but about the Son; the Spirit\'s ministry is inherently Christological.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: "And you also must testify, for you have been with me from the beginning." The disciples\' witness is grounded in their firsthand experience of the incarnate Son — they were with him "from the beginning" of the ministry (cf. Acts 1:21–22). The Spirit testifies and the disciples testify: the witness to Christ is double, trinitarian and human. The church\'s apostolic testimony is the human dimension of the Spirit\'s own witness. The Spirit does not replace the eyewitnesses; he empowers them and establishes the truth of what they say.</p>'
  },
  "16": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: "All this I have told you so that you will not fall away." The purpose of the farewell discourses — the foot-washing, the vine, the love command, the promise of the Spirit — is pastoral: the disciples should not stumble when persecution comes. The foreknowledge the Son has shared is not meant to produce anxiety but stability. Those who know in advance what is coming, why it is happening, and who will sustain them through it are equipped to endure what those without this knowledge would abandon under pressure.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "the time is coming when anyone who kills you will think they are offering a service to God." The most chilling form of religious persecution: violence committed in the name of divine service. This anticipates both the Jewish persecution of early Christians (Acts 7:58 — the stoning of Stephen) and the Roman persecutions framed as civic-religious duty. Jesus warns of this specifically so that when the disciples face religiously motivated killing, they understand that the persecutors are acting from the same darkness that crucified the Son — mistaking the will of the world-ruler for the will of God.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "They will do such things because they have not known the Father or me." The ignorance of the persecutors — they do not know the Father or the Son — is their only partial excuse and their comprehensive condemnation simultaneously. They act in the name of God while remaining ignorant of who God is; they persecute the disciples of the Son while denying the Son. The one who truly knows the Father would recognize the Son; the one who truly knows the Son would recognize those who bear his name. The root of religious violence is theological ignorance of this depth.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "so that when their time comes you will remember that I warned you about them." The pastoral function of prophecy — equipping the disciples to interpret their suffering when it arrives — is grounded in the foreknowledge of Christ who sees what is coming and prepares his followers for it. The remembered prophecy is not a consolation but a reorientation: when the disciples suffer, they should not conclude that God has abandoned them but that Christ\'s prediction has been confirmed, which grounds continued trust.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "None of you asks me, Where are you going?" The disciples are absorbed in their grief at the prospect of Christ\'s departure (v6) and not asking the question that would reframe their experience. Where he is going — to the Father — is the key to understanding why his departure is not loss but gain. The Evangelist uses the disciples\' silence to open the teaching of vv7–11: the direction of departure matters more than the fact of it. Going to the Father enables the sending of the Spirit, which enables everything that follows.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme: "you are filled with grief because I have said these things." The disciples\' grief is genuine and human. The Evangelist does not dismiss it; Jesus addresses it directly in what follows. The grief that fills the disciples is the grief of those who have understood that departure is coming but not yet understood what the departure accomplishes. The same grief-to-joy transition that Jesus describes for childbirth (v21) will be their experience: the grief of the cross will become the joy of the resurrection morning.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct revelation: "it is for your good that I am going away. Unless I go away, the Advocate will not come to you; but if I go, I will send him to you." The departure of the incarnate Christ is the precondition for the Spirit\'s coming, and the Spirit\'s presence is a greater good than the physical presence of the pre-crucifixion Jesus. The earthly Jesus was geographically limited; the Spirit-mediated Christ is universally present. The glorified Christ sending the Spirit enables the mission that the unglorious Christ cannot alone accomplish. This is the logic of Pentecost: the ascension of the Son enables the descent of the Spirit.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A direct revelation: "When he comes, he will prove the world to be in the wrong about sin and righteousness and judgment." The Spirit\'s ministry in the world is a forensic one — establishing the truth about three realities that the world has misunderstood. The three convictions the Spirit works correspond to the three Christological claims that the world has denied: the world is wrong about what sin is (v9), what righteousness is (v10), and who has been judged (v11).</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct revelation: "about sin, because people do not believe in me." Sin in the Johannine framework is not primarily moral failure but the rejection of the Son. The ultimate sin — the one the Spirit must convict the world about — is unbelief in Christ. All other sins are symptoms of this root: the refusal to receive the one God has sent. The Spirit convicts the world that its fundamental posture toward God is wrong because it is a posture of rejection toward the Son whom God gave for its life (3:16).</p>',
    "10": '<p>A direct revelation: "about righteousness, because I am going to the Father, where you can see me no longer." The Son\'s going to the Father is the Father\'s vindication of his righteousness — the resurrection and ascension are the Father\'s declaration that the Son was righteous and his accusers were wrong. The Spirit convicts the world about righteousness by pointing to the ascended Christ: the one they condemned as a blasphemer has been received by God. The righteousness the Spirit reveals is not moral perfection in the abstract but the vindicated person of Christ, declared righteous by the Father\'s raising him.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A direct revelation: "about judgment, because the prince of this world now stands condemned." The cross — which looked like Christ\'s condemnation — is in fact the condemnation of the prince of this world. The Spirit convicts the world that the judgment it feared (its own condemnation) has been executed on the adversary, and the one it executed (Christ) has been vindicated. The cross is the moment of the world-ruler\'s defeat (12:31), and the Spirit reveals this reversal to the world: the one who seemed to lose is the victor; the one who seemed to win stands condemned.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "I have much more to say to you, more than you can now bear." The restraint of the Son in the pre-resurrection period is itself a form of pastoral care: the disciples cannot yet receive what the Spirit will bring after the glorification. The limitation is not the Son\'s but the disciples\': they are not yet constituted to receive the full revelation. The coming of the Spirit — and the resurrection that precedes it — will be the transformation that makes them able to receive what the earthly discourses can only begin to communicate.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct revelation: "when he, the Spirit of truth, comes, he will guide you into all the truth." The Spirit\'s guiding into truth is the Christological continuation of what Jesus has been doing in the farewell discourses — making the Father known through the Son. The Spirit does not add to the content of the Son\'s revelation but leads the disciples into the full depth of what the Son has disclosed. The truth the Spirit reveals is not new truth but the same truth — the whole truth of Christ — that the disciples were not yet able to bear (v12). The canon of apostolic Scripture is the Spirit\'s fulfillment of this promise.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct revelation: "He will glorify me because it is from me that he will receive what he will make known to you." The Spirit\'s work is inherently Christological: he glorifies the Son by taking what belongs to the Son and making it known. The Spirit does not point to himself; he points to Christ. Every true work of the Spirit in the world — conviction of sin, regeneration, illumination, sanctification — is a work that points to and glorifies Christ. The Spirit is the Spirit of Christ (Rom 8:9; 1 Pet 1:11), and his ministry is the extension of Christ\'s own glorification.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct revelation: "All that belongs to the Father is mine. That is why I said the Spirit will receive from me what he will make known to you." The Son\'s identity with the Father — "all that belongs to the Father is mine" — is stated with maximum comprehensiveness. The shared possession of the Father and Son includes the truth the Spirit mediates: what the Father has, the Son has; what the Son has, the Spirit discloses. The chain of revelation (Father → Son → Spirit → disciples) is grounded in the Trinitarian sharing of all things between Father and Son.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: "In a little while you will see me no more, and then after a little while you will see me." The "little while" before and after refers to the death (a little while to the crucifixion) and the resurrection (a little while back to appearing). The disciples will experience the loss of seeing Jesus (the crucifixion and burial) and the restoration of sight (the resurrection appearances). The time frame is exact: three days. The disciples cannot yet grasp this, which is why their confusion in vv17–18 is genuine.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A theme: the disciples\' mutual puzzlement — "what does he mean by \'a little while\'?" — shows that the resurrection framework has not yet been given to them. They are trying to interpret the statement within what they know, and what they know does not include the resurrection. The Evangelist preserves their incomprehension as historically accurate and theologically significant: the disciples who will become the apostles are right now unable to understand what their own preaching will later hinge on.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A theme: "We don\'t understand what he is saying." The honest admission of incomprehension is the posture the Evangelist has consistently valued over false confidence. The disciples do not pretend to understand; they confess they do not. This is the same posture that opened the space for revelation in 13:25 (the Beloved Disciple asking plainly about the betrayer) and 14:5 (Thomas asking plainly about the way). Jesus\' response (v19) will address the question rather than rebuking it.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: Jesus perceives their desire to ask — divine insight into their hearts (2:25; 6:61). He addresses the question before they articulate it, which is itself a sign of who he is. The response in vv20–22 will not explain the "little while" analytically but will reframe it with the birth-pain image: the grief and the joy are the same event experienced in two moments. The Son\'s pastoral response to their confusion is not a lecture but an image that holds the grief and the joy together.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "You will weep and mourn while the world rejoices. You will grieve, but your grief will turn to joy." The cross will be the moment of the disciples\' maximum grief and the world\'s apparent victory. The resurrection will reverse both: the disciples\' grief becomes joy; the world\'s rejoicing will discover it was premature. The reversal is the pattern of the entire biblical narrative: the Servant\'s suffering becomes the many\'s justification (Isa 53:11); the cross becomes resurrection; death becomes life. Isaiah 35:10 anticipated this: "sorrow and sighing will flee away."</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "A woman giving birth to a child has pain because her time has come; but when her baby is born she forgets the anguish because of her joy." The birth-pain image for the transition from suffering to glory is the OT\'s consistent metaphor for the messianic age (Isa 26:17–19 — resurrection from the dead through birth-pain; Isa 66:7–9 — Zion\'s birth-pain producing a nation). The disciples\' grief at the cross is the birth-pain that precedes the joy of the resurrection. The anguish is real; it is also temporary and productive — it is the birth of the new creation.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct revelation: "I will see you again and you will rejoice, and no one will take away your joy." The resurrection appearances are the fulfillment of this promise — Jesus will see them again, and their joy will be the indestructible joy of those who have seen the risen Lord. "No one will take away your joy" is the promise of the permanence of resurrection-joy — not dependent on circumstances, not revocable by the world, not subject to the returning grief of loss. The joy of the resurrection is the eschatological joy that remains.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "In that day you will no longer ask me anything. Truly, truly, I tell you, my Father will give you whatever you ask in my name." The post-resurrection era is the era of direct access — the disciples will not need to ask Jesus questions (their understanding will be complete through the Spirit) but will ask the Father directly in Jesus\' name. The mediation of prayer through Christ\'s name is not an obstacle but the ground of the access: the disciples\' relationship to the Father is established through the Son, and prayer in his name means praying as those who belong to the Son.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: "Until now you have not asked for anything in my name." The era of praying "in my name" has not yet opened — it will open at the resurrection and the giving of the Spirit. The disciples are at the threshold of a new mode of prayer that requires the crucified, risen, and ascended Christ to be its ground. The completeness of joy that prayer in Christ\'s name produces is the fullness of the covenant relationship now available through the Son\'s finished work.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: "a time is coming when I will no longer use this kind of language but will tell you plainly about my Father." The figurative speech of the vine, the birth-pain, the "little while" will give way to plain disclosure after the resurrection — both through the post-resurrection teaching (Acts 1:3 — "he appeared to them over a period of forty days and spoke about the kingdom of God") and through the Spirit\'s illumination of what the figurative language was pointing to. The resurrection is the hermeneutical key that converts parabolic speech into plain revelation.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: "In that day you will ask in my name. I am not saying that I will ask the Father on your behalf." The statement clarifies the nature of Christ\'s intercession: he does not have to overcome the Father\'s reluctance or compensate for the Father\'s distance from the disciples. The Father himself loves those who belong to the Son. The Son\'s intercession is not needed to make the Father willing; the Father is already willing because the disciples are already his. The intercession is the formal channel of the relational access that the Father himself desires to give.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: "the Father himself loves you because you have loved me and have believed that I came from God." The Father\'s direct love for the disciples is grounded in their love for and belief in the Son. The relational chain is complete: those who are united to the Son by love and faith are united to the Father who loves the Son. The disciples\' faith is not merely a technique for accessing divine power; it is the relational bond that places them within the sphere of the Father\'s own covenantal love.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A direct revelation: "I came from the Father and entered the world; now I am leaving the world and going back to the Father." The fullest single-sentence statement of Christological ontology in the Gospel: the complete arc of the incarnation — origin in the Father, descent into the world, and return to the Father. The four movements (from, entered, leaving, going back) correspond to the preexistence, incarnation, death/ascension, and glorification at the Father\'s right hand. The disciples have been hearing this in figurative language; here it is plain. The Son who comes from the Father is the same Son who returns to the Father — no loss of identity in the descent, no diminishment in the return.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A theme: "Now you are speaking clearly and without figures of speech." The disciples feel they have finally understood — the plain statement of v28 seems to remove all ambiguity. Their confidence is touching and, as the next verses will show, premature. They understand the statement; they have not yet understood the person. The comprehension of Christological propositions is not the same as the faith that endures through the cross. Their confidence will be tested within hours.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: "Now we can see that you know all things and that you do not even need to have anyone ask you questions. This makes us believe that you came from God." The disciples\' statement of belief — "we believe that you came from God" — is a correct Christological confession. The ground they give (his foreknowledge) is also correct. But Jesus\' response (v31) does not ratify their confidence; he questions its durability. The belief that cannot survive the cross is belief in a Christ who has not yet been crucified.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of God: "Do you now believe?" The question is gentle but searching. The Evangelist presents Jesus as testing the quality of the disciples\' faith — not whether they have correct beliefs but whether those beliefs are rooted deeply enough to endure what is coming. The question anticipates the scattering of v32: the faith they are claiming will be tested within the hour. The question is also for the reader: the faith evoked by the farewell discourses must be tested by the passion narrative that follows to see whether it is the faith John 20:31 calls for.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A revelation of God: "you will be scattered, each to your own home. You will leave me all alone. Yet I am not alone, for my Father is with me." The scattering of the disciples is both predicted and absorbed into the Son\'s certainty of the Father\'s presence. Zechariah 13:7 ("strike the shepherd, and the sheep will be scattered") will be fulfilled (cited in Matt 26:31; Mark 14:27). But the Son is not left desolate even in the abandonment: "I am not alone, for my Father is with me." The one who is about to be abandoned by his disciples and cry out from the cross (Matt 27:46) nevertheless grounds his identity in the Father\'s unbroken presence. Johannine theology does not diminish the reality of the cross; it frames it within the Son\'s eternal relationship to the Father.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A direct revelation: "I have overcome the world." The verb is perfect tense (<em>nenikēka</em>) — a completed action with ongoing results. The victory is accomplished before the cross, not after it, because the cross is not the world\'s victory over the Son but the Son\'s defeat of the world\'s power over humanity. The entire system of sin, death, judgment, and the adversary\'s dominion is overcome in the person of the Son who is about to walk through it all without being held by it. The peace he promises (v27) is grounded in this accomplished victory. The disciples will "have trouble" in the world (the word for trouble is the same as the disciples\' grief at the cross), but they can "take heart" because the one who has overcome the world is within them.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'john')
    merge_comm(existing, JOHN)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'john', existing)
    print('John 14–16 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
